First, (review and edit) then run setup.sh, you may want to change SETUP_BASE, the database setup will consume about ~200G of disk space.

For reference, I used Fedora Cloud Image as the base VM image.

Setting up VM (optional)
========================
Download the image:
wget https://download.fedoraproject.org/pub/fedora/linux/releases/39/Cloud/x86_64/images/Fedora-Cloud-Base-39-1.5.x86_64.qcow2

Set root password (For `virt-sysprep` tool, do `dnf install guestfs-tools -y`):
virt-sysprep -a /data/volumes/Fedora-Cloud-Base-39-1.5.x86_64.backup.qcow2 --root-password password:fedora

You may need to expand the qcow2 image or attach a external image/disk. In my case I attached a standalone disk and ran following command after VM is launched (vdb is my externel disk):
mkdir /var/mongo-test
mount /dev/vdb /var/mongo-test/


Run the benchmark (run this in test environment, eg. the VM above)
=================
Clone this repo (with submodule):
git clone --recurse-submodules https://github.com/ryncsn/emm-test-project.git

If already cloned without submodules:
git submodule update --init

Run the setup script:
cd emm-test-project/mongo-cluster
./setup.sh

It will show some prompts, and ask which Mongo Image to use, I used this one:
docker.io/library/mongo:6

After setup.sh is done, run the command it instruct you to run (setup the DB user/password).

setup.sh will also initialize the py-tpcc submodule, and build a Docker image
(py-tpcc-runner) based on python:2.7 with pymongo installed, for running py-tpcc
since Python 2.7 is no longer available through dnf on recent Fedora releases.

For data preparing: (only need to run once, will consume ~200G of space, you may
use mongodb.config.* depends on which replica is master)
./run.sh load

For benchmark: (run multiple time for benchmark)
./run.sh run

For both load and benchmark in one go:
./run.sh both

run.sh will automatically start the mongo cluster if it's not already running.

Resource limits and tuning:
./run.sh --memlimit 48G --iops 5000 run        # default limits
./run.sh --memlimit 32G --iops 10000 run        # custom limits
./run.sh --memlimit 0 --iops 0 run              # no limits
./run.sh -w 100 -c 10 -d 300 run                # fewer warehouses, shorter run
./run.sh --config mongodb.config.1 run           # use a different replica
./run.sh --help                                  # full usage
